1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,100
 So, we're going to take a look at some of these object-oriented implementations over time.

2
00:00:04,100 --> 00:00:06,600
 I've already talked about the Python inspiration.

3
00:00:06,600 --> 00:00:12,500
 I flipped Python and C++ in the early days, because at least Python we kind of know.

4
00:00:12,500 --> 00:00:22,300
 C++ is 1980, Java in '95, JavaScript in '95, PHP in 2000, and then C# in 2001.

5
00:00:22,300 --> 00:00:27,100
 So, here's the example that I showed you before, talked about it before.

6
00:00:27,100 --> 00:00:32,300
 You have a constructor, double underscore, init, double underscore, with self as the first parameter.

7
00:00:32,300 --> 00:00:37,100
 Self.x, again, the key thing is self is by convention.

8
00:00:37,100 --> 00:00:40,100
 Self is not a language construct.

9
00:00:40,100 --> 00:00:45,300
 It just so happens that the first parameter of method calls is to the instance,

10
00:00:45,300 --> 00:00:48,900
 and we almost exclusively use the word self for that.

11
00:00:48,900 --> 00:00:58,900
 That is a very early 1991 implementation of an object-oriented syntax on top of a mostly procedural language.

12
00:00:58,900 --> 00:01:04,200
 Now, if we take a look at C++, C++ was initially implemented as a pre-processing pass,

13
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:07,700
 and it sort of did sort of one-for-one textual transformations,

14
00:01:07,700 --> 00:01:12,500
 and so class was not a keyword in the C language.

15
00:01:12,500 --> 00:01:16,500
 Public, that's not a keyword in the C language.

16
00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:23,600
 There was syntactic transformation that kind of transformed it into C and then run it through the C compiler.

17
00:01:23,600 --> 00:01:26,500
 And so we say, I mean, and this is pretty elegant,

18
00:01:26,500 --> 00:01:32,700
 and you can absolutely see how Python was inspired by C++.

19
00:01:32,700 --> 00:01:39,100
 So, class, point, open curly brace, double x and y are the attributes,

20
00:01:39,100 --> 00:01:45,200
 and the constructor by convention is the exact, it's a function that has no type.

21
00:01:45,200 --> 00:01:48,700
 The constructor is the exact same name as the class.

22
00:01:48,700 --> 00:01:55,500
 So in this case, I've got point with an uppercase P, and then the constructor parameters come in.

23
00:01:55,500 --> 00:02:01,400
 Now, the interesting thing is you have to declare as double x and y as the attribute variables,

24
00:02:01,400 --> 00:02:06,400
 and then within the function, you can think of the double x, y as almost like extern scope,

25
00:02:06,400 --> 00:02:08,700
 means they're global across all functions.

26
00:02:08,700 --> 00:02:14,000
 So you have this weird thing where you can't have a parameter like you could in Python.

27
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:18,900
 You can't have a parameter of the same name as an instance variable or you'll be confused.

28
00:02:18,900 --> 00:02:23,500
 And so you'll notice I called the xc and yc as my parameter variables

29
00:02:23,500 --> 00:02:26,900
 so that I know that those are parameters in the constructor.

30
00:02:26,900 --> 00:02:31,600
 And so I can copy xc into x and yc into y.

31
00:02:31,600 --> 00:02:36,700
 And it also means if you look at the dump code, you see like you don't have to say self.x,

32
00:02:36,700 --> 00:02:39,700
 you don't, you just say x and y because x and y are doubles.

33
00:02:39,700 --> 00:02:43,600
 They're instance-wide, extern variables, as it were.

34
00:02:43,600 --> 00:02:46,100
 And the same is true in the origin function.

35
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:49,300
 That's returning the square root of x squared plus y squared.

36
00:02:49,300 --> 00:02:53,300
 You don't have to have self or this or anything else.

37
00:02:53,300 --> 00:03:00,800
 So if we take a look at the main program on that first line, point pt open paren 4.0, 5.0,

38
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:08,200
 we are both allocating a point instance and calling the constructor and setting it up.

39
00:03:08,200 --> 00:03:14,300
 Then we use the dot syntax pt dot dump open paren close paren semicolon to dump it out.

40
00:03:14,300 --> 00:03:20,700
 And then we can call pt.origin and then that will return us a double.

41
00:03:20,700 --> 00:03:30,100
 And so you'll see this sort of dot syntax that is become pretty common in every language that comes afterwards.

42
00:03:30,100 --> 00:03:31,200
 So let's take a look at Java.

43
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:39,300
 Now, recall that Java was inspired both by C and C++ and really wanted to be like the super language.

44
00:03:39,300 --> 00:03:45,000
 And you see that it looks a lot like C++, but it does introduce the concept of this.

45
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:49,800
 So that it scopes the external variables that are the instance variables.

46
00:03:49,800 --> 00:03:55,000
 You access an instance variable by saying this.x and this.y rather than just x and y.

47
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:58,900
 And I think it's actually more elegant this way.

48
00:03:58,900 --> 00:04:03,900
 So we say public class point and then double x comma y, which are the instance variables.

49
00:04:03,900 --> 00:04:10,000
 And then the constructor is using the C++ convention of point with no type.

50
00:04:10,000 --> 00:04:13,200
 Double x and double y are the two parameters.

51
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:18,500
 This.x equals x and this.y equals y. Close curly breaks.

52
00:04:18,500 --> 00:04:27,400
 Now, I like this better because using this keeps me from having to make weird function parameter variable names.

53
00:04:27,400 --> 00:04:32,900
 I can make them what I want to be and using this is the way that we contextualize that.

54
00:04:32,900 --> 00:04:38,700
 So if we look at the dump method, we see the use of this.

55
00:04:38,700 --> 00:04:41,700
 And this is not just by convention.

56
00:04:41,700 --> 00:04:43,600
 This is a language element.

57
00:04:43,600 --> 00:04:46,000
 So this is the pointer.

58
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:55,400
 You can see from the output it actually prints out the class that it is and some kind of reference like ID like thing.

59
00:04:55,400 --> 00:05:02,000
 And so Java actually, if you start printing objects out, it tells you what its type and what instance it is.

60
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:05,900
 It's not necessarily an address, but it probably is related to the address somehow.

61
00:05:05,900 --> 00:05:08,000
 But then we print out this.x and this.y.

62
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:15,200
 And then if we look at the double origin method, we see it's this.x times this.x plus this.y times this.y.

63
00:05:15,200 --> 00:05:19,600
 So you see the sort of use of this throughout.

64
00:05:19,600 --> 00:05:26,800
 Then if we look at the main program, we see point pt equals new point 4.0, 5.0.

65
00:05:26,800 --> 00:05:31,900
 This is where we see the use of this new operator where you're saying, look, call the constructor.

66
00:05:31,900 --> 00:05:33,200
 And I like this.

67
00:05:33,200 --> 00:05:38,300
 I like the sense that you're calling the constructor on purpose.

68
00:05:38,300 --> 00:05:40,400
 You're not calling it implicitly.

69
00:05:40,400 --> 00:05:43,900
 And then you end up with pt as the instance of this object.

70
00:05:43,900 --> 00:05:47,000
 And so for me, this feels pretty good.

71
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:52,000
 pt.dump is a good example of calling a method within the instance.

72
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:55,200
 And pt.origin is similar.

73
00:05:55,200 --> 00:05:58,700
 If we take a look at JavaScript and recall that JavaScript is the weird one.

74
00:05:58,700 --> 00:06:03,000
 JavaScript did not take its inspiration from C++.

75
00:06:03,000 --> 00:06:12,300
 C++'s syntax was kind of influenced by the fact that it was initially a preprocessor to the language C.

76
00:06:12,300 --> 00:06:19,100
 And some computer scientists would think that that's a rather impure way to think about object orientation.

77
00:06:19,100 --> 00:06:26,100
 And so JavaScript, when it was created, the idea was to be more pure in object orientation.

78
00:06:26,100 --> 00:06:35,800
 And so the concept of first class functions, because it has first class functions, there is no class keyword.

79
00:06:35,800 --> 00:06:40,500
 The class keyword was really useful when it was a preprocessor.

80
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:45,100
 The thing that JavaScript does take is the concept of this.

81
00:06:45,100 --> 00:06:51,700
 Now, the interesting thing is if you look at everything on the screen from function point to the closed curly brace,

82
00:06:51,700 --> 00:06:54,600
 this is the constructor.

83
00:06:54,600 --> 00:06:57,500
 The constructor constructs everything.

84
00:06:57,500 --> 00:07:02,800
 It constructs the attribute variables and it actually constructs all the methods as well.

85
00:07:02,800 --> 00:07:08,100
 So if we look at the line this.party equals function openPrin, closedPrin, openCurly brace,

86
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:14,500
 we are setting, in a sense, an attribute variable to source code.

87
00:07:14,500 --> 00:07:15,900
 This is an anonymous function.

88
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:20,500
 There's no name to the function, so most functions are named, but this function has no name.

89
00:07:20,500 --> 00:07:21,700
 That's a JavaScript thing.

90
00:07:21,700 --> 00:07:23,500
 It's a first class function thing.

91
00:07:23,500 --> 00:07:30,500
 We are basically not running that function with the two lines of this.x equals this.x plus one and console.log blah blah blah.

92
00:07:30,500 --> 00:07:31,600
 Those lines aren't running.

93
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:40,900
 They're being compiled and then the code to execute that is being assigned into the attribute variable party.

94
00:07:40,900 --> 00:07:42,300
 So it doesn't run it.

95
00:07:42,300 --> 00:07:44,600
 It reads it and stores it in party.

96
00:07:44,600 --> 00:07:51,100
 You can literally later print out this.party and you will see the source code to that function.

97
00:07:51,100 --> 00:07:53,700
 And the same is true for this.dump.

98
00:07:53,700 --> 00:07:57,800
 It's an assignment statement and then similarly this.origin.

99
00:07:57,800 --> 00:08:05,300
 And you see within those methods, you see this.x and this.y, which is taken directly from job.

100
00:08:05,300 --> 00:08:11,300
 We also see the concept of new in pt equals new point 4.0 5.0.

101
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:13,000
 We are explicit and I like this.

102
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:19,100
 I like the idea of saying, please call the constructor from the point class and pass these two variables in.

103
00:08:19,100 --> 00:08:25,600
 And then we see the C++ inspired syntax of pt.dump to call a method in the pt instance

104
00:08:25,600 --> 00:08:30,700
 and pt.origin to call a method in instance.

105
00:08:30,700 --> 00:08:40,700
 If we look at PHP, now the key to PHP was PHP is a procedural language when it was created in 94

106
00:08:40,700 --> 00:08:45,500
 and then it became an object oriented language in PHP 4 and then 5.

107
00:08:45,500 --> 00:08:46,900
 It was late to the party.

108
00:08:46,900 --> 00:08:57,000
 So it could be inspired by everything, by JavaScript, by Java, by C++, by Simula, by Scheme, all of those things.

109
00:08:57,000 --> 00:09:02,600
 And so the PHP object orientation is kind of pretty as a result of that.

110
00:09:02,600 --> 00:09:12,100
 Now, one of the things that happens in PHP is it's got some weird language syntax things in that variables have to start with a dollar sign.

111
00:09:12,100 --> 00:09:15,800
 Thank you, Pearl, for that.

112
00:09:15,800 --> 00:09:19,500
 And the dot operator is used for concatenation in PHP.

113
00:09:19,500 --> 00:09:26,400
 So we couldn't use the dot operator to look up instance variable or a method inside of an instance.

114
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:32,000
 PHP borrowed the C arrow operator, which is minus sign, greater than.

115
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:41,500
 Now, the interesting thing is, is if you go back to pointers, the arrow operator is what you do when you have a pointer to a structure.

116
00:09:41,500 --> 00:09:50,000
 And so in some ways, that is a throwback to C in a beautiful way because I think kind of under the covers and as we shall see

117
00:09:50,000 --> 00:10:00,800
 when we are starting to implement object orientation in C ourselves, we're going to see that pretty much we get pointers to an instance is a pointer to something rather than a thing.

118
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:06,000
 And so we see this arrow x equals dollar x in the constructor.

119
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:16,200
 We see the constructor is a double underscore construct so that PHP kind of use the single underscore and double underscore as sort of metadata about the meaning of things

120
00:10:16,200 --> 00:10:18,300
 and double underscore are things you're not supposed to call.

121
00:10:18,300 --> 00:10:19,200
 They're supposed to be private.

122
00:10:19,200 --> 00:10:25,100
 And then we have a function dump and you see the concepts of this inside of dump and origin.

123
00:10:25,100 --> 00:10:26,600
 You see this in the main code.

124
00:10:26,600 --> 00:10:29,200
 You see dollar pt equals new point four or five.

125
00:10:29,200 --> 00:10:32,600
 Oh, well, it's following the new from Java and others.

126
00:10:32,600 --> 00:10:37,500
 And then we call pt arrow dump dump and then dollar pt arrow origin.

127
00:10:37,500 --> 00:10:45,200
 It pretty much works like most of the other ones, except that you'd never use dot because dot is concatenation in PHP.

128
00:10:45,200 --> 00:10:51,500
 And I'll be honest, I love dot for concatenation, except for the fact that PHP is different than every other language that I use.

129
00:10:51,500 --> 00:10:54,500
 Every other language uses plus for concatenation of strings.

130
00:10:54,500 --> 00:10:56,600
 Now, C# is a 2001.

131
00:10:56,600 --> 00:11:08,000
 So C# was inspired kind of by everything. And so you see that C# is clearly a very C++ oriented but with some Javaness to it.

132
00:11:08,000 --> 00:11:14,000
 So you see the double XY in class, which is the two instance variables.

133
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:17,200
 You also see that not there's no use of this.

134
00:11:17,200 --> 00:11:26,500
 And so you see that we have to name the parameters differently because X and Y are in effect global across the entire class.

135
00:11:26,500 --> 00:11:28,900
 And then we have, you know, void dump there.

136
00:11:28,900 --> 00:11:32,700
 And then we see that it's just using X and Y. No need to use this.

137
00:11:32,700 --> 00:11:38,100
 It's it's tough for me to decide which of these two ways I like better.

138
00:11:38,100 --> 00:11:42,600
 I guess that this is this feels more explicit to me.

139
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:45,200
 So I like Java and JavaScript in that respect.

140
00:11:45,200 --> 00:11:47,200
 Self and I like self also.

141
00:11:47,200 --> 00:11:52,600
 If we look at the origin function, we see X star X and plus Y star Y.

142
00:11:52,600 --> 00:11:54,700
 And so we don't use need to use this.

143
00:11:54,700 --> 00:12:02,800
 We again see a very Java oriented point PT equals new point open pren 4.0 comma 5.0 point dot dump.

144
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:09,800
 We're using the dot operator to look at instance variables and methods within the within the class and then point dot origin.

145
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:19,700
 So now that we looked at sort of a survey of the different kinds of object oriented languages that are that are today and we can sort of see how they derived ideas from one another.

146
00:12:19,700 --> 00:12:23,900
 Now we're going to actually try to build an object in a non-object oriented language.

147
00:12:23,900 --> 00:12:27,800
 So we're going to build like a Python object in C.

